Definition: from {{h6051}}; cloudy; Anani, an Israelite; Anani.

from {{h6026}}; luxurious; delicate.

a primitive root; properly, to eye or (generally) to heed, i.e. pay attention; by implication, to respond; by extension to begin to speak; specifically to sing, shout, testify, announce; give account, afflict (by mistake for {{h6031}}), (cause to, give) answer, bring low (by mistake for {{h6031}}), cry, hear, Leannoth, lift up, say, × scholar, (give a) shout, sing (together by course), speak, testify, utter, (bear) witness. See also {{h1042}}, {{h1043}}.

a primitive root (possibly rather identical with {{h6030}} through the idea of looking down or browbeating); to depress literally or figuratively, transitive or intransitive (in various applications, as follows); abase self, afflict(-ion, self), answer (by mistake for {{h6030}}), chasten self, deal hardly with, defile, exercise, force, gentleness, humble (self), hurt, ravish, sing (by mistake for {{h6030}}), speak (by mistake for {{h6030}}), submit self, weaken, × in any wise.
passive participle from the same as {{h6025}}; borne (as fruit); Anub, an Israelite; Anub.
feminine of {{h6035}}; mildness (royal); also (concretely) oppressed; gentleness, meekness.
probably from {{h6030}}; an answer; Anah, the name of two Edomites and one Edomitess; Anah.
or (by intermixture with {{h6041}}) עָנָיו; from {{h6031}}; depressed (figuratively), in mind (gentle) or circumstances (needy, especially saintly); humble, lowly, meek, poor. Compare {{h6041}}.
from {{h6035}}; condescension, human and subjective (modesty), or divine and objective (clemency); gentleness, humility, meekness.
from {{h6031}}; affliction; affliction.
a primitive root; to be (causatively, make) deep (literally or figuratively); (be, have, make, seek) deep(-ly), depth, be profound.

a primitive root; to associate; by implication, to overshadow (by huddling together); become dim, hide.

from {{h5998}}; toiling; concretely, a laborer; figuratively, sorrowful; that laboureth, that is a misery, had taken (labour), wicked, workman.
a primitive root; properly, to carve, i.e. fabricate or fashion; hence (in a bad sense) to worry, pain or anger; displease, grieve, hurt, make, be sorry, vex, worship, wrest.
from {{h6095}}; a tree (from its firmness); hence, wood (plural sticks); carpenter, gallows, helve,   pine, plank, staff, stalk, stick, stock, timber, tree, wood.

from {{h6080}}; dust (as powdered or gray); hence, clay, earth, mud; ashes, dust, earth, ground, morter, powder, rubbish.
from {{h6080}}; a fawn (from the dusty color); young roe (hart).

; a primitive root; meaning either to be gray or perhaps rather to pulverize; used only as denominative from {{h6083}},; to be dust; cast (dust).

from {{h6009}}; deep (literally or figuratively); (× exceeding) deep (thing).

a variation of {{h6089}}; an idol (as fashioned); also pain (bodily or mental); idol, sorrow, × wicked.
from {{h6087}}; an (idolatrous) image; idol, image.
from {{h6087}}; a (hired) workman; labour.
from {{h6087}}; worrisomeness, i.e. labor or pain; sorrow, toil.
from {{h6087}}; a idol; also, a pain or wound; sorrow, wound.

from {{h6095}}; the spine (as giving firmness to the body); backbone.

from {{h3289}}; advice; by implication, plan; also prudence; advice, advisement, counsel([-lor]), purpose.
or עָצֻם; passive participle of {{h6105}}; powerful (specifically, a paw); by implication, numerous; feeble, great, mighty, must, strong.

from {{h6030}}; answer; Anath, an Israelite; Anath.

the same as {{h6060}}; Anak, a Canaanite; Anak.

probably for {{h5288}}; Aner, a Amorite, also a place in Palestine; Aner.
patronymically from {{h6061}}; an Anakite or descendant of Anak; Anakim.
from an unused noun (denoting a place in Palestine; from an unused root of uncertain meaning); an Ophnite (collectively) or inhabitants of Ophen; Ophni.
from {{h5774}}; an eyelash (as fluttering); figuratively, morning ray; dawning, eye-lid.
from {{h6075}}; a tumor; also a mound, i.e. fortress; emerod, fort, strong hold, tower.
the same as {{h6076}}; Ophel, a ridge in Jerusalem; Ophel.
